    en: "New York does not offer true expungement — the state does not erase most criminal records. What New York offers is sealing. Under Criminal Procedure Law 160.59 and the 2023 Clean Slate Act (effective November 2024), certain convictions can be sealed from public view. A sealed record stays in state and federal criminal databases but does not appear on most employment and housing background checks. Dismissed cases and cases ending in the person's favor are sealed automatically under Criminal Procedure Law § 160.50. Old marijuana convictions are actually expunged (erased) under the 2021 Marijuana Regulation and Taxation Act. Understanding the difference matters because many people search for 'expungement' when New York's tool is sealing."
